# shellcheck shell=bash disable=SC2034,SC1091
# Config file for sourceable shell scripts; unused warnings expected.

# ==============================================================================
# ORADBA BasEnv Integration
# ==============================================================================
#
# This file demonstrates how to integrate OraDBA with TVD BasEnv / DB*Star
# in a coexistence configuration where BasEnv maintains control of Oracle
# environment variables (ORACLE_SID, ORACLE_HOME, ORACLE_BASE, etc.).
#
# Three integration modes are supported:
#
#   1. standalone      - No BasEnv detected; OraDBA has full control
#   2. basenv          - BasEnv detected; minimal coexistence (auto-default)
#   3. basenv-maximal  - BasEnv detected; extended aliases (opt-in)
#
# ==============================================================================
# INSTALLATION
# ==============================================================================
#
# Copy this file to:
#
#   - ${ETC_BASE}/basenv.conf
#       (applied globally to all Oracle instances on this host)
#   or
#   - ${ETC_BASE}/sid._DEFAULT_.conf or ${ETC_BASE}/sid.<SID>.conf
#       (applied to a specific SID or default to all SIDs)
#
# where ${ETC_BASE} is BasEnv's configuration directory (typically /etc/basenv
# or /opt/basenv/etc).
#
# ==============================================================================
# MINIMAL MODE (basenv) - Default
# ==============================================================================
#
# In basenv mode, OraDBA is loaded but restricted to prevent conflicts with
# BasEnv-managed Oracle variables. OraDBA libraries and ORADBA_* variables
# are available; Oracle variables remain under BasEnv control.

# Load OraDBA libraries and ORADBA_* variables
# Oracle variables (ORACLE_SID, ORACLE_HOME, ORACLE_BASE, TNS_ADMIN, etc.)
# remain under BasEnv control and are NOT modified by OraDBA
if [[ -f "${TVD_BASE}/oradba/bin/oraenv.sh" ]]; then
    source "${TVD_BASE}/oradba/bin/oraenv.sh"
fi

# ==============================================================================
# MAXIMAL MODE (basenv-maximal) - Optional Extension
# ==============================================================================
#
# In basenv-maximal mode, OraDBA additionally loads safe, non-conflicting
# aliases (sq_oradba, sdba, sora, etc.) that enhance the command-line
# experience without overriding BasEnv's Oracle variable management.
#
# To enable basenv-maximal mode, set this in oradba_local.conf instead:
#
#   export ORADBA_COEXIST_MODE="basenv-maximal"
#
# This is not set by default to preserve the principle of minimal intrusion
# and allow explicit opt-in by the administrator.

# ==============================================================================
# WHAT ORADBA DOES NOT TOUCH IN COEXISTENCE MODE
# ==============================================================================
#
# When in basenv or basenv-maximal mode, OraDBA explicitly avoids:
#
#   ORACLE_SID        - Set and managed by BasEnv
#   ORACLE_HOME        - Set and managed by BasEnv
#   ORACLE_BASE        - Set and managed by BasEnv
#   TNS_ADMIN          - Set and managed by BasEnv
#   NLS_LANG           - Set and managed by BasEnv
#   SQLPATH order      - BasEnv entries remain first
#   PATH order         - Oracle executables remain under BasEnv control
#   PS1                - Prompt customization not applied
#   BE_* variables     - All BasEnv internal variables remain untouched
#
# These restrictions ensure that BasEnv's environment configuration remains
# authoritative and OraDBA acts as a tool supplement rather than an environment
# manager.

# ==============================================================================
# FURTHER CUSTOMIZATION
# ==============================================================================
#
# For additional OraDBA configuration (debugging, logging, feature flags),
# consult oradba_local.conf or oradba_core.conf for available variables.
#
# Common customization points:
#
#   ORADBA_LOAD_ALIASES=true      - Enable/disable alias loading
#   DEBUG=1                        - Enable debug logging
#   ORADBA_NO_ORACLE_MODE=false   - Set automatically; indicates no Oracle DB
#
# Example: Create oradba_local.conf with:
#
#   export ORADBA_COEXIST_MODE="basenv-maximal"
#   export DEBUG=1
#   export ORADBA_LOAD_ALIASES=true

# ==============================================================================
# EOF
# ==============================================================================
